<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
04/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   CHAMORRO ASSUMED Nicaragua's presidency, ending Sandinista
rule.
   After a decade of U.S. hostility toward the nation's
leftist leaders, the 60-year-old publisher took the oath of
office in Managua before about 20,000 people. In her
inaugural speech, Chamorro, a conservative elected in
February, declared a political amnesty and ended the military
draft. She also said that Gen. Humberto Ortega, the
ex-president's brother, would head the armed forces, but that
she would be the defense minister. In Washington, Bush made
Nicaragua eligible again for Export-Import Bank financing and
restored its full authority to export sugar to the U.S.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Chamorro's decision to retain Gen. Ortega is expected to
rile the anti-Sandinista Contra rebels, who have signed an
accord to disarm by June 10.
   ---
   The shuttle Discovery's astronauts sent the Hubble Space
Telescope on a 15-year mission to explore the far reaches of
the universe. After the crew overcame some balky gear, the
telescope was placed into orbit and began circling the Earth
at an altitude of 380 miles -- high above the atmosphere that
has limited the view of ground-based devices.
   ---
   A woman stabbed West Germany's leading opposition
candidate, Oskar Lafontaine, during a campaign rally in
Cologne. Officials said the 46-year-old politician, chosen by
the Social Democratic Party to challenge Kohl in December's
national elections, was in serious condition after being
wounded in the neck. The assailant was arrested.
   ---
   Lithuania is urgently seeking direct trade links with
Soviet regions as a way of skirting the Kremlin's cutoff of
energy supplies to the republic, which proclaimed its
independence March 11. Gorbachev, meanwhile, traveled to a
Ural Mountain industrial center in an effort to ease worker
concern over the transition to a market economy.
                                                                                                       

   Bush rejected criticism of his refusal to act against the
Soviet Union for its crackdown on Lithuania, saying he has
"strong support from the American people." The president's
decision was denounced in Lithuania as a gesture of
appeasement toward Moscow. A spokesman said the U.S.
sympathized with Vilnius's "frustration."
   ---
   Shiite Moslem leader Musawi urged pro-Iranian kidnappers
to continue holding their Western hostages, saying the U.S.
had sabotaged efforts to win the release of other captives.
Musawi, believed to have played a role in Sunday's release of
Polhill, cited the House's passage Tuesday of a resolution
endorsing Jerusalem as Israel's capital.
   ---
   Chinese Premier Li sought to minimize suggestions of an
ideological rift between Beijing and Moscow, but made clear
that the Communist powers remained divided over how to "build
socialism." Li, on a visit to the Soviet Union, also said
there won't be a repeat of last spring's protests in China.
   ---
   India and Pakistan discussed separatist violence in
Kashmir, and agreed that tensions should be reduced and
confrontation avoided. The foreign ministers of the two
nations, who met in New York, issued a communique urging
continuing contacts.
   ---
   A car bomb exploded near a truck carrying anti-terrorist
police in the Colombian city of Medellin, killing at least
six people. Responsibility for the attack wasn't immediately
claimed, but cocaine traffickers have pledged to kill police
officers in a campaign against Bogota's crackdown on drugs.
   ---
   The House approved a bill giving federal regulators the
power to revoke a bank's charter or withdraw its deposit
insurance if it and its directors or officers are convicted
of laundering money.
   ---
   Israel's Peres acknowledged defeat after five weeks of
attempting to form a government following the collapse of the
coalition led by Prime Minister Shamir, which had refused to
enter peace talks with Palestinians. The Labor Party leader
said he would formally abandon his effort today.
   ---
   Rival Christian forces battled in residential areas of
eastern Beirut and in outlying towns, killing at least 15
people. It was considered the worst fighting in more than a
month as the Lebanese Forces militia and Gen. Aoun's troops
pressed the struggle for control of Lebanon's Christian
enclave.
   ---
   The Soviet legislature adopted a program to resettle
another 200,000 people from areas irradiated in the Chernobyl
nuclear power plant explosion. The move came on the eve of
today's fourth anniversary of the accident. Official reports
have said 31 people were killed, and more than 100,000 people
have been evacuated from the area.
   ---
   Died: Dexter Gordon, 67, tenor saxophonist who helped
define the be-bop style of jazz and was nominated for an
Oscar for his starring role in the 1986 film "Round
Midnight," in Philadelphia, of kidney failure.
</TEXT>
