<HL>
   Goodyear Profit Fell
   78% in First Quarter;
   Higher Costs Cited
</HL>
<DATE>
04/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   GT
</CO>
<IN>
AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   AKRON, Ohio -- Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co.'s first-quarter
net income plunged 78%.
   The earnings drop stemmed from price competition, higher
costs from increased advertising and compensation, and lower
tire demand from auto manufacturers. That lower demand
resulted in temporary Goodyear plant closings.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Akron, Ohio-based tire maker announced earlier this
month that it would report sharply reduced earnings; the
decline was in line with analysts' projections. Net was $20.9
million, or 36 cents a share, compared with the year-ago
$94.5 million, or $1.64 a share. Sales were $2.69 billion, up
slightly from $2.64 billion a year earlier.
   Harry W. Millis, an analyst with McDonald &amp; Co.,
Cleveland, said he expected first-quarter net to be between
25 cents and 50 cents a share. "Profit was in line with what
I expected," he said.
   Goodyear said previously that its oil pipeline would
decrease earnings by 50 cents a share, and the pipeline's
losses weren't reflected in the 1989 first-quarter report.
Profits were also squeezed by Brazilian government efforts to
brake inflation in that country, efforts which hurt the
company's large subsidiary there. Goodyear is also incurring
start-up costs on a tire plant in Canada.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900426-0140
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900426-0140.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   ITT Net Rose 27%
   In First Quarter
   On a Special Gain
   ----
   By James C. Hyatt
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   ITT
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- ITT Corp. said net income rose 27% in the
first quarter, results it called "better than expected."
   Net income rose to $253 million, or $1.88 a share, from
$200 million, or $1.40 a share. The latest quarter included
the previously reported after-tax gain of $47 million, or 33
cents a share, on the sale of the company's investment in
Compagnie Generale d'Electricite. Without the gain, net
income would have risen 3%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Rand V. Araskog, chairman and chief executive officer,
said operating results, or income before taxes and interest,
for all businesses except electronic parts were equal to or
better than year-earlier results.
   Sales rose 2% to $4.93 billion from $4.83 billion. The
year-earlier quarter included $139 million in sales from
businesses that have since been divested. "Despite the lower
results in some of our businesses, 1990 is off to a good
start," Mr. Araskog said.
   ITT said defense business operating income improved
because of increased contract margins and product shipments.
Automotive gains in Europe were offset by softness in North
American markets. Fluid-technology results were flat, while
pulp and timber income improved, reflecting favorable profit
margins from log sales and higher pulp volume. Income from
electronic components declined substantially, reflecting
"continuing competitive pressures within the connector and
semiconductor businesses resulting in lower sales and
margins."
   ITT said its equity from Alcatel N.V. "rose dramatically;"
Alcatel is a European telecommunications-equipment joint
venture with Compagnie Generale d'Electricite.
   Earnings from service businesses declined because of "the
difficult business climate in the U.S. during the quarter."
Operating results at the Hartford insurance business rose due
to higher investment income and improved life-insurance
operations, offset by "continued deterioration" in casualty
underwriting.
   ITT Financial had "a substantial decline" because of
increased provisions for consumer-loan losses from "portfolio
control actions and an increase in personal bankruptcies."
Results declined at the ITT Sheraton hotel operations.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
ITT closed at $52, up 62.5 cents.
</TEXT>
