<HL>
   Money Funds Yields
   Were Flat Again
   In the Latest Week
   ----
   By Georgette Jasen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23
</SO>
<IN>
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
</IN>
<LP>
   Yields on money-market mutual funds remained flat in the
week ended Tuesday, despite recent increases in short-term
interest rates.
   The average seven-day compound yield on taxable funds
stayed at 7.99% for the third consecutive week, according to
IBC/Donoghue's Money Fund Report. Compound yields assume
reinvestment of dividends.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the 428 taxable funds tracked by Donoghue's fell
for the fourth consecutive week, to $381.7 billion from
$382.1 billion. Brenda Malizia Negus, editor of the
newsletter, which is based in Holliston, Mass., attributed
the latest decline to withdrawals for tax purposes.
   Meanwhile yields on many other short-term investments
rose. The yield on six-month Treasury bills sold at Monday's
auction, for instance, shot up to 8.35% from 8.18% the week
before, while three-month bills rose to 8.05% from 7.97%.
Banxquote Money Markets, a New York information service,
reported earlier this week that yields on certificates of
deposit at major banks rose across the board in the week
ended Tuesday.
   Average maturity of the funds' investments remained at a
relatively long 44 days for the second consecutive week,
following several weeks of 45 days; maturities have ranged
from 29 to 53 days in recent years. Funds invest in such
things as commercial paper, short-term Treasury securities
and certificates of deposit.
   "We may see average maturities shorten if {portfolio}
managers are taking this talk of an inflation threat
seriously," said Ms. Negus of Donoghue's. Shorter maturities
typically are considered a sign that money managers think
interest rates are rising, because they can then latch onto
higher yields sooner. Conversely, longer maturities usually
are thought to indicate declining rates.
   The average seven-day simple yield remained at 7.69% in
the week ended Tuesday, while the 30-day simple yield inched
up to 7.69% from 7.68%. The average 30-day compound yield
moved to 7.99% from 7.98%.
   Yields on tax-free money funds rose by about 0.10
percentage point in the week ended Tuesday, although assets
fell. The average seven-day compound yield on tax-exempt
funds, for example, jumped to 5.74% from 5.63%. The latest
week's yield is equivalent to 7.97% for investors in the 28%
tax bracket and 8.57% for those paying 33%.
   Assets of the 220 tax-free funds tracked by Donoghue's
fell by about $916 million, to $76.6 billion. Average
maturity shortened to 43 days from 45.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900426-0127
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900426-0127.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Wednesday's Markets:
   Stocks Snap
   Five-Session
   Losing Spell
   ---
   Norton Takeover Pact
   Adds to Momentum;
   Bonds, Dollar Drop
   ----
   By Douglas R. Sease
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   Stock prices rebounded in light trading, snapping a
five-session losing streak. But bond prices continued to
erode modestly and the dollar weakened.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 11.94 to 2666.44 in
thin trading. Long-term Treasury bonds lost about an eighth
of a point, or about $1.25 for each $1,000 of face amount.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts said apparent firming in the bond market early in
the day got stock prices off to a good start. Later, news
that Norton had accepted a $90-a-share takeover offer from
Saint-Gobain of France provided enough confidence to keep
stock prices up after bonds began slipping.
   The modest stock market rally was welcome relief from the
drumbeat of slumping prices that carried the Dow Jones
Industrial Average down 4% in the past five sessions. But
many analysts dismissed yesterday's gains as a mere technical
rally that won't endure. They argue that investors remain
worried about the course of interest rates and inflation and
aren't likely to see stocks as the best place to put money
until it is clear that interest rates have stabilized.
   Bond traders share the pessimistic interest-rate outlook.
Although bond prices rose briefly yesterday, traders remained
worried about inflation and economic growth. They're bracing
for the initial report Friday on first-quarter gross national
product, which is expected to be at least double the 1.1%
growth posted in the fourth-quarter of 1989 and perhaps as
much as 3%. They also expect inflation data that are part of
the GNP report to show inflation rising.
   Longer term, traders are concerned that the Treasury's
quarterly refunding auction next month will put further
pressure on bond prices. And they're debating the likelihood
the Federal Reserve will push short-term interest rates
higher before the May auction. As the economy picks up steam
and inflation rises, the odds increase that the Fed will
raise rates in a bid to slow the economy and bring inflation
back under control.
   In major market action:
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices climbed in light trading. Volume on the New
York Stock Exchange totaled 133.5 million shares. Advancing
issues on the Big Board were ahead of decliners 774 to 664.
                                                                                                       

   Bond prices were off. The yield on the Treasury's
benchmark 30-year issue rose to 8.97%.
                                                                                                       

   The dollar was lower. In late New York trading, the U.S.
currency was quoted at 1.6785 marks and 158.75 yen compared
with 1.6980 marks and 158.93 yen Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
