<HL>
   Marketing:
   For Perrier,
   New Woes
   Spring Up
   ----
   By Thomas R. King
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   F.PRR
</CO>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
BEVERAGES (BVG)
</IN>
<LP>
   Just a week after the Food and Drug Administration forced
the bottlers of Perrier water to drop the words "naturally
sparkling" from its labels, the French company is coming
under fire from New York state health officials over its use
of the term "sodium-free."
   New York state health officials said a sample of Perrier
water provided by the company contained too much sodium for
the company to use the term "sodium-free" under FDA
regulations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Their complaint throws a wrench into the planned relaunch
of the product. Late yesterday, worried Perrier officials
were in Albany in an effort to persuade health officials to
let Perrier return to store shelves today, as the company had
promised.
   Source Perrier S.A. has been scrambling to get its product
back on the market and restore consumer confidence following
the global recall in February of the popular French mineral
water. The recall occurred after tiny amounts of benzene, a
known carcinogen, were found in small samples of the trendy
drink.
   The FDA, which had signed off on Perrier's U.S. relaunch,
said it intends to examine the data that Perrier supplied to
New York officials.
   FDA regulations allow water marketers to use the term
"sodium-free" if there are five milligrams or less of sodium
per eight-ounce serving, or 21.2 milligrams per liter. One
test of a sample that Perrier Group of America Inc. provided
to New York state revealed a sodium level of 21.6 milligrams.
   The state officials also expressed anger over reports that
bottles of Perrier have already returned to the market in New
York, even though the state hasn't given a go-ahead on the
reintroduction. "We have not returned their certification at
this point," said William Stasiuk, director of the state's
Center for Environmental Health, indicating that the return
in New York is still up in the air. New York would be the
first state to see Perrier back on the shelves.
   Mr. Stasiuk said the sodium levels, like the previous
traces of benzene, don't pose any significant health risk.
But, he said, "people who are on severely sodium-restricted
diets should be cautioned" about the amount of sodium in
Perrier.
   Kim Jeffrey, Perrier's senior vice president of marketing,
said Perrier conducted many tests of its new water through
five independent laboratories. Two of those samples,
including the sample that registered 21.6 milligrams of
sodium, were sent to New York state. When New York officials
asked about the sodium levels, Perrier sent 79 additional
samples. Of those, one additional sample had a sodium level
that exceeded federal standards, the rest were all
satisfactory, Mr. Jeffrey said.
   "We conform to the guidelines for the sodium-free
designation," he added. He said the average sodium level for
all the samples was 17.1 milligrams per liter.
   New York state officials also asserted yesterday that some
samples of old Perrier water have turned up in stores on New
York's Long Island. Mr. Stasiuk said that although officials
haven't conducted a "scientific health department search,"
the codes on the bottles and the absence of a special label
indicated the bottles predated the world-wide recall of
Perrier. The reintroduced Perrier would carry a label saying
"nouvelle production."
   In a letter to the health officials, Mr. Jeffrey said
Perrier Group, the French company's U.S. arm, based in
Greenwich, Conn., plans to run a special ad in Long Island's
Newsday newspaper warning consumers to buy only Perrier that
has the "nouvelle production" labels.
   Mr. Jeffrey acknowledged that Perrier is having difficulty
getting into the New York market, but he said the problems
generally involve "administrative issues relative to issues
surrounding the entire bottled-water category." He declined
to elaborate.
   Mr. Jeffrey said he didn't know that Perrier was already
being sold in some delicatessens and supermarkets in New York
state. He said that the company's distributors cover the
tri-state area of New York, New Jersey and Connecticut and
added that the problem was probably in the distribution
chain, adding: "I have not authorized the product to be sold
in New York . . . period."
   After it announced its recall, Perrier attributed the
benzene contamination to improper filtration of its carbon
dioxide gas. The gas, Perrier says, naturally contains small
amounts of benzene. The filters apparently became overloaded
after Perrier switched to a new gas source. Perrier says it
has improved its filtration process, and the FDA says tests
indicate the water is no longer contaminated.
   That done, Perrier ran into a whole different problem last
week, when the FDA told the company it couldn't put
"naturally sparkling" on labels. The agency based its ruling
on the fact that Perrier takes the water and the carbon
dioxide separately out of its spring. The carbonation
therefore is artificial, the FDA said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900426-0073
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900426-0073.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media -- Advertising:
   Media Sector in Recession; Few Admit It
   ----
   By Joanne Lipman
</HL>
<DATE>
04/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   BN GREY WNEWS WPPGY
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   In media circles, everyone's thinking about it, but almost
no one wants to say it: The business is in a recession.
   Newspaper advertising is in the deepest slump in recent
memory. Magazine advertising is faring no better. The outlook
for broadcast advertising is unclear. Yet no one dares use
the dreaded "R" word.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "It's like the old saying: If it walks like a duck, talks
like a duck and looks like a duck, maybe we should start
calling it a duck," says Spencer Plavoukos, chairman and
chief executive officer of the New York office of Interpublic
Group's Lintas ad agency. "We may not have reached the
criteria for what an official recession is, but everyone has
hit the bunkers. I don't see a major trending away from where
we ended up in 1989. I don't see {a turnaround} in 1990."
   According to the indicators filtering out from Washington,
the economy as a whole isn't in a recession -- usually
considered two consecutive quarters of declining inflation --
adjusted gross national product. But media advertising, which
closely mirrors the economy, suggests that the indicators
aren't telling the full story. "The question is, have we,
despite what all the indicators say, already slipped into a
recession?" asks John Morton, a media analyst with Lynch,
Jones &amp; Ryan. "Certainly the media business is having one."
   Clearly, the outlook for most major media is bleak.
Newspaper publishers, after a dismal 1989, have been caught
by surprise by an even worse 1990 so far. In March, many were
alarmed by a falloff in advertising even steeper than the
previous two months. Publishers now are expecting at best
flat ad revenue for 1990, and perhaps a small uptick in 1991
-- although some are skeptical even of that.
   At the just-concluded meeting of the American Newspaper
Publishers Association in Los Angeles, the mood was downbeat.
Newspaper advertising has been battered primarily by a
drop-off in retail advertising, which typically accounts for
half of all newspaper ads. Many publishers at the meeting
questioned whether retail advertising will ever return to
former levels, to the heady days before the bankruptcy-law
filings of L.J. Hooker Corp., Campeau Corp.'s U.S. unit and
other retailers.
   Classified advertising, meanwhile, accounting for about
40% of most newspaper advertising, has shown virtually no
growth in most major markets. That weakness is particularly
troubling to publishers, because classified ads are the most
profitable type of newspaper advertising. "We are in a
recession," says Valerie Salembier, president of the New York
Post. "But no one wants to use that word."
   The situation is similar in the magazine business, where
first-quarter ad pages dropped an average 3.5%, according to
the Magazine Publishers of America. Individual declines were
staggering, ranging from a 24.3% drop at Family Media's Savvy
Woman to an 18.4% plunge at Time Warner's People. Ad revenue
at Time Warner's magazine group, which also includes Sports
Illustrated, Time and Fortune magazines, was off about 6% to
7% in the first quarter, the company says. Magazines' major
problem: weak automotive and tobacco advertising.
   Reginald K. Brack, who heads up Time Warner's magazine
company, concedes that the first quarter was "terrible," and
says that while the second and third quarters look "a little
stronger, I'm still not looking at a big turn upward in ad
spending." But he contends that the word recession "is
probably too strong," since previous quarters had shown
increases. "If you went two or three quarters like the first
quarter, that would be a recession," he says.
   Still, Mr. Brack says, "it's going to be a real tough year
no matter where you are in advertising, whether it's an ad
agency or newspapers or TV."
   The broadcast business currently is something of a wild
card. Robert Coen, director of forecasting for Interpublic's
McCann-Erickson ad agency, believes that network TV, and in
fact all mass media, have "been in a recession since 1985."
In inflation-adjusted dollars, network TV ad revenue actually
declined by 5% to 6% in 1989, he says. The networks have been
battered by an explosion of other options, like cable TV and
videocassettes, as well as by a decline in audience levels.
   The big question now is what will happen to demand and
prices in the 1990 fall season; the "upfront" buying season
for fall begins around June. Advertising executives are
reluctant to speculate about where network advertising will
head in a year already notable for its miserable ad
environment.
   The networks "are in a critical situation. It all depends
on how the business climate and economy is by midyear when
the upfront is negotiated," says Mr. Coen. "I think they'll
probably just about hold their head above water."
   Mr. Coen believes the problem with the networks, along
with other mass media, is that in previous years, they
responded to strong demand by overinflating their prices, and
now are suffering through an inevitable correction. So why
won't anyone come out and call a spade a spade, if this is
indeed a recession? Says Mr. Coen, "I guess it's kindness."
   ---
   Ad Notes. . . .

   NEW ACCOUNTS: Borden Inc.'s Snacks &amp; International
Consumer Products Division awarded its snack-food account to
W.B. Doner &amp; Co. The account, with billings of less than $5
million, encompasses 13 snacks including Krunchers potato
chips, as well as four Wise brand snack foods. Jordan,
McGrath, Case &amp; Taylor had resigned the account several
months ago . . . Grey Advertising's Grey Entertainment &amp;
Media unit was tapped to create advertising for the New York
Yankees. Billings weren't disclosed . . . After a review, the
California Lottery, based in Sacramento, elected to keep its
$7 million Hispanic ad account at Casanova Pendrill
Publicidad, Irvine, Calif.
                                                                                                       

   ACQUISITION: Leading National Advertisers, which tracks ad
spending, said it acquired Radio Expenditure Reports Inc.,
based in Mamaroneck, N.Y., which tracks radio ad spending.
Terms weren't disclosed.
                                                                                                       

   WHO'S NEWS: WPP Group's J. Walter Thompson Co. named Hugh
Trenkamp general manager of its regional advertising group, a
field marketing network with about $120 million in U.S.
billings and clients, including 45 regional Ford dealer
groups. He also becomes executive vice president of the
agency's U.S. unit . . . D'Arcy Masius Benton &amp; Bowles named
Irwin Gotlieb world-wide director of broadcast and
programming, and Rino Scanzoni director of national broadcast
for the agency's U.S. unit.
