<HL>
   Business Brief -- West Point-Pepperell Inc.:
   Auction of Fabrics Division
   Dropped Due to Low Bids
</HL>
<DATE>
04/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7
</SO>
<CO>
   WPM
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc., West Point, Ga., said it has
pulled its apparel fabrics division off the auction block
because of low preliminary bids.
   In its annual report filed with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, the textile concern said it had
solicited offers for the division -- its most profitable
behind household fabrics -- but stopped pending an
improvement in the financial markets and its parent company's
financial position.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   West Point Acquisition Corp., the company set up by
William F. Farley to purchase West Point-Pepperell last year
for about $1.56 billion, is in dire straits. Earlier this
month, West Point Acquisition defaulted on $796 million in
bank debt and on interest payments on $705 million in
subordinated debt.
   The company reiterated in the filing that it is
negotiating with its bankers, led by Wells Fargo &amp; Co. and
Bankers Trust Co., and has made an exchange offer to its
bondholders in an effort to restructure debt incurred in the
acquisition.
   Last month, the company got only $410 million in cash and
notes for its Cluett, Peabody &amp; Co. unit, after projecting it
would fetch more than $600 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900426-0050
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900426-0050.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Cyprus Minerals Co.:
   Net Fell 63% in 1st Period;
   Lower Copper Prices Cited
</HL>
<DATE>
04/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CYM
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
NON-FERROUS METALS (ONF)
</IN>
<LP>
   Cyprus Minerals Co. reported net income fell 63%, on a
1.4% decline in revenue, due to lower copper and molybdenum
prices and higher costs at some of its mines.
   For the first quarter, net income declined to $30.1
million, or 65 cents a share, compared with $80 million, or
$1.96 a share, in the year-earlier period. Year-ago earnings
included a $5 million gain from the sale of clay operations.
Revenue declined to $429.5 million, from $435.8 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Denver-based Cyprus said it is seeing improvement in
copper production costs, but the mining company doesn't
expect 1990 earnings to be higher than 1989 earnings. For all
of 1989, Cyprus earned $250.1 million on revenue of $1.79
billion.
   The large earnings drop indicates how vulnerable the
company's earnings still are to fluctuations in copper
prices, despite efforts to diversify into other kinds of
mining ventures over the past five years. Each one cent
increase in copper production costs, or one cent decrease in
the price of copper, results in a 10-cent a share decline in
annual earnings for Cyprus, said R. Wayne Atwell, analyst at
Goldman Sachs &amp; Co.
</TEXT>
