</DOCID>
<HL>
   Heard on the Street:
   Torchmark's Proxy Fight Against American
   General Hinges on the Concerns' Performance
   ----
   By David B. Hilder
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<CO>
   AGC TMK
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
INSURANCE (INS)
HEARD ON THE STREET (HRD)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- How's this for a simple choice: You can cast
your lot with a company whose stock price more than tripled
in the past five years. Or you can side with a company in the
same industry whose stock price gained a paltry 20% in the
same period.
   That's the essence of the choice facing shareholders of
American General -- the laggard mentioned above -- which is
the object of a takeover bid and proxy fight by Torchmark,
whose stock price has been soaring.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The performance records of the two companies make a
powerful argument for Torchmark, according to several
insurance analysts and takeover-stock speculators. But a
variety of other factors, including the unusual takeover
tactics that Torchmark has employed, have raised doubts about
whether Torchmark will win the vote at American General's
annual meeting scheduled for Wednesday.
   Those doubts, combined with the long regulatory delays
that usually accompany a hostile bid for an insurance
company, have kept American General's stock price well below
the $50 a share in cash and stock that Torchmark offered but
quickly withdrew last month.
   Yesterday, however, American General shares jumped 1 1/8
to close at 37 7/8, helped by renewed enthusiasm for takeover
stocks. Sparking that enthusiasm was Norton's agreement to
sell itself to Saint-Gobain for $90 a share, $15 a share more
than BTR PLC's hostile $75 bid.
   Meanwhile Torchmark shares sagged 1/8 to close at 45 1/8.
Since Torchmark announced its bid, its shares have fallen
because of fears about the dilution and increased debt load
that an acquisition of American General would cause.
   The case for Torchmark is that it's a lean, well-managed
company whose rising earnings and heavy stock buy-backs have
boosted its share price. "Torchmark has done a good job of
maximizing value to shareholders," says Carol Manning, a
Smith Barney insurance analyst who has neutral ratings on
both stocks. She adds: "American General shares have been
trading at a greater than average relative discount to the
market because the return to shareholders has been below
average for the life insurance industry."
   In the 1980s, American General did a lot of buying and
selling. It added more life insurance companies, shed
property-casualty units and expanded its consumer finance
business by acquiring a Manufacturers Hanover subsidiary for
$685 million in 1988. It has been slow to cut costs but
recently became more aggressive, promising annual savings of
$40 million by putting together certain Florida and Tennessee
operations. American General has also been buying back stock,
but less aggressively than Torchmark.
   Torchmark is nominating five directors of the six up for
election at American General's annual meeting. The board has
a total of 15 members who serve staggered terms. Torchmark
has said that if it wins, it will make a new acquisition
proposal.
   "We think the American General shareholders have nothing
to lose by supporting the Torchmark proxy fight," Ms. Manning
says.
   Analyst Ronald P. McIntosh at Fox-Pitt Kelton is
recommending both stocks. He believes American General will
restructure even if it remains independent, and Torchmark
will be able to cut costs and sell assets at American General
if it wins the company.
   "We have called Torchmark's the best management in the
life insurance industry," Mr. McIntosh says.
   Torchmark's administrative expenses are about 16% of
premiums in home-service life insurance compared with 24% at
American General, Mr. McIntosh says. American General argues
that commission expenses should also be included and that on
this basis its costs are only five percentage points higher
than its rival's. American General says its expenses are
higher because it operates in 25 states compared with
Torchmark's five.
   Harold S. Hook, American General's chairman, argues that
Torchmark won't be able to repeat its success with his
company. "I don't think you can draw a straight line from any
of the specifics and make a case against AG," says Mr. Hook,
adding that he expects to win the proxy vote.
   Mr. McIntosh of Fox-Pitt predicts victory for Torchmark,
although he says some institutions have been puzzled by
Torchmark's quick withdrawal of its takeover bid. By
retreating, however, Torchmark may have made it easier to
press its proxy fight without getting approval in advance
from state insurance regulators.
   The regulators, however, could still force Torchmark to
withdraw its slate before the meeting or before the results
of the vote are announced. The major hurdles are hearings in
Tennessee today and tomorrowand in Hawaii tomorrow. There's
also a federal appeals court hearing in New Orleans on
Monday. Takeover-stock speculators rate the chances of a vote
taking place on Wednesday as a little better than a tossup.
   ---
   American General
   (NYSE; Symbol: AGC)
                                                                                                       

   Business: Insurance and consumer finance
                                                                                                       

   Year ended Dec. 31, 1989:
   Net Income: $464.1 million; $3.76 a share*
                                                                                                       

   First quarter, March 31, 1989:
   Per-share earnings: 90 cents vs. 77 cents
                                                                                                       

   Average daily trading volume:
   407,280 shares
                                                                                                       

   Common shares outstanding: 121.4 million
                                                                                                       

   *Includes net gain of $53 million; or 43 cents a share
from sale of certain properties and $51 million; or 42 cents
a share of profit from discontinued operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900426-0026
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900426-0026.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb
   Sees Per-Share Profit
   Surpassing $3.25 in '90
</HL>
<DATE>
04/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   BMY
</CO>
<IN>
DRUG MANUFACTURERS (DRG)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Bristol-Myers Squibb Co. said it agrees with
analysts' estimates that per-share 1990 profit will be
between $3.25 and $3.30, adding that earnings dilution from
its merger last year should end by late 1991 or 1992.
   In 1989, the company earned $747 million, or $1.43 a share
-- including a $693 million charge related to the merger last
October of Bristol-Myers and Squibb -- on sales of $9.2
billion. Last week, the giant pharmaceutical and health
care-products company posted a 19% rise in first-quarter
earnings, to $409.1 million, or 78 cents a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Richard L. Gelb, chairman and chief executive officer,
said that although there are many areas where the two
companies have been able to combine operations,
"Bristol-Myers and Squibb didn't merge in order to save
money. Nevertheless, by the end of next year, we expect to
have achieved savings sufficient to make up in full for the
dilution. From that point on, former Bristol-Myers shares
will have the same earning power as before the merger, with
the incremental earning power of Squibb added."
   The company's statement was apparently issued because of
investment community interest about how the merger is
proceeding.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading,
Bristol-Myers closed at $52.875 a share, up 25 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900426-0025
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900426-0025.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
04/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   NORTON AGREED to be acquired for $90 a share, or about
$1.9 billion, by French glassmaker Saint-Gobain, a surprising
rescue of the Massachusetts abrasives maker from hostile
suitor BTR of Britain. BTR, which offered $75 a share, ended
its proxy fight against Norton and said it wouldn't top
Saint-Gobain's bid. Norton's stock surged $13.50, to $88.75.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   More foreigners are buying up U.S. companies, in part
because American buyers are having problems getting bank
loans or junk-bond financing.
   ---
   Bush won't designate Japan as an unfair trading partner,
aides said, a shift from the tough U.S. stance of a year ago.
Trade Representative Carla Hills said that "Japan has moved
further this year than any other country" in lowering trade
barriers.
   ---
   B.A.T agreed to sell its Saks Fifth Avenue chain for about
$1.5 billion to Investcorp, a low-profile partnership of Arab
investors. The group is taking a big gamble on an industry
that has bankrupted other foreign investors.
   ---
   Environmentalists claimed a symbolic victory against Exxon
at its annual meeting. Six shareholder proposals on the
environment failed but won more votes than expected.
   ---
   Safeway underwriters slashed the price of stock offering
that is due to begin trading today. The supermarket chain
went private in 1986 and is one of the crown jewels of
Kohlberg Kravis.
   ---
   Michael Milken may be vulnerable to the many shareholder
suits filed against him, some attorneys say. But lawyers for
Drexel's ex-junk bond chief, who pleaded guilty to six felony
counts Tuesday, dismiss the idea.
   ---
   The SEC is cracking down on program traders who have
exploited a regulatory loophole for as long as four years.
The move may curb index arbitrage, a type of program trading.
   ---
   A consumer-protection bill that requires nutrition
labeling on all packaged foods was approved by a Senate
panel, which brushed aside objections from the food industry.
   ---
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange is trying to halt the further
sale of warrants that let investors bet on the market's
direction. U.S. underwriters and the Amex are expected to
comply.
   ---
   Ralph Ingersoll closed the St. Louis Sun, the ambitious
daily newspaper he launched in September.
                                                                                                       

   Gannett Foundation said it may sell its 10% stake in the
Gannett newspaper chain, citing an IRS rule.
   ---
   Harcourt Brace may sell some of its publishing operations
to Thomson to help pay off its massive debt from a 1987
recapitalization.
   ---
   Procter &amp; Gamble's profit soared a higher-than-expected
30% in the latest quarter, as sales rose 13%.
   ---
   Control of Penrod Drilling has apparently been won by a
group that includes the influential Texas investor Richard
Rainwater.
   ---
   Merrill Lynch's private placement group has been hit by
key departures just as the market for privately placed
securities is set to explode.
   ---
   Britain's trade deficit worsened surprisingly in March,
rattling London markets and stirring concern about Thatcher's
inflation policy.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 133,480,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2666.44, up 11.94; transportation 1136.38, up 2.31; utilities
206.30, up 0.25.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3229.48, off
4.07.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.37, off 0.28;
spot index 135.32, off 0.22.
   Dollar: 158.75 yen, off 0.18; 1.6785 marks, off 0.0195.
</TEXT>
